00:56:00.719 --> 00:56:06.560
the response. And lots of frameworks have their own way of making those requests.

00:56:06.719 --> 00:56:10.399
Okay. Last question I'll answer here in the last minute that we've got, what is the advantage of

00:56:10.399 --> 00:56:16.479
using an R API versus Shiny apps? Really good question. Shiny applications are really best

00:56:16.479 --> 00:56:20.800
suited for like human interaction, right? So if I've got a Shiny application, I'm going to come

00:56:20.800 --> 00:56:27.520
in here and I'm going to interact with it as an individual, right? As a API, it's not necessarily

00:56:27.520 --> 00:56:32.159
expected that users are going to come in here and interact with the API this way. They might do it

00:56:32.159 --> 00:56:36.399
a little bit, right? Just to kind of check some things, but in most cases, an API is going to be

00:56:36.399 --> 00:56:41.840
interacted with programmatically. So I might build a plumber API so that another tool that my company

00:56:41.840 --> 00:56:47.199
developed can use my model or can use the business logic that I've implemented in my API. I might

00:56:47.199 --> 00:56:52.800
use a Shiny app so that another user can view my model, if that makes sense, right? So the

00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:57.199
distinction here is who's the end user. In one case for Shiny, it's another human that's

00:56:58.159 --> 00:57:02.320
interacting with my application. For APIs, it's most likely another tool

00:57:02.320 --> 00:57:10.560
that's interacting with my application or with my API.

